To update your requirements.txt file after installing new packages, the standard Python approach is to use the pip freeze command. This command lists all the packages currently installed in your active virtual environment along with their exact version numbers.

Here is how you do it:

Make sure your virtual environment is activated (you should see (venv) in your terminal).
Navigate to your Backend folder where the requirements.txt lives.
Run the following command:
bash
pip freeze > requirements.txt
This will overwrite the requirements.txt file with a complete, up-to-date list of everything installed in your environment.

A quick tip for your specific setup: Since you created a setup.py file to turn your project into a CLI package, you should also manually add any new core packages to the install_requires list inside c:\Users\Debus\OneDrive\Desktop\ComfyUIAutomation\Backend\setup.py. This ensures that if you ever install the CLI on a different machine using pip install -e ., it knows to grab the new dependencies!

