Yes, absolutely! I know exactly what you mean. You want to compile your entire Python application into a single .exe file so you can drop it anywhere (or share it) and run it without needing to install Python, set up virtual environments, or use pip.

To do this, we will use PyInstaller. It bundles your Python scripts and all your installed libraries (requests, websocket-client) into one neat executable.

Here is exactly how to do it:

1. Install PyInstaller
   Make sure your virtual environment is still activated ((venv) should be visible in your terminal), and run:

bash
pip install pyinstaller 2. Build the Executable
Navigate to your Backend folder in the terminal and run this command:

bash
pyinstaller --onefile --name comfy-auto app.py
The --onefile flag tells it to bundle everything into a single .exe file.
The --name comfy-auto flag sets the output file name to comfy-auto.exe.
app.py is the entry point it will start from. 3. Find your .exe
Once the process finishes, PyInstaller will have created a few new folders (build and dist) and a .spec file. You will find your ready-to-use standalone executable inside the dist folder: c:\Users\Debus\OneDrive\Desktop\ComfyUIAutomation\Backend\dist\comfy-auto.exe

You can now move comfy-auto.exe anywhere on your computer. To run it, open a terminal in the folder where you placed it and run:

bash
comfy-auto.exe --mode jobs --jobs jobs.csv
(Important Note: Because your pipeline.py currently looks for example.json using a hardcoded local path, make sure example.json is in the same folder as your .exe when you run it!)

